-TEXT INSIDE ARTICLE-
Social justice group Sonke Gender has lambasted Spur for cancelling the panel meant to handle issues around racism concerning an incident at The Glen's Texamo Spur earlier this year.

The organisation has been heavily involved in the matter since it happened in March.

"Now we are deeply disappointed in the cancellation of the panel. It is clear that Spur bowed to the racist pressure applied by Afriforum and Solidariteit," the organisation's Child Rights and Positive Parenting portfolio manager Wessel van den Berg said on Friday.

He said Both organizations supported the boycott of Spur on the premise that the restaurant should have also banned Lebohang Mabuya as they did Nico Viljoen.

"Lebohang was in fact the one being attacked. Their support for Viljoen demonstrates an expression of systemic racism, embedded in white privilege, which ignores the ascribed power due to race, of the aggressor Nico Viljoen," he said.

He also said the company was overlooking an important issue.

"In our assessment Spur is condoning violence and racism by stepping back from a serious analysis and course of action.' van den Berg said.

"They have moved away from finding a lasting solution to this challenge."

The panel was set up by the restaurant chain after a video of two patrons arguing after their children were in a squabble. In a heated exchange, the white man threatens the black woman which caused public outrage.

The man was then banned by Spur leading to backlash from minority rights groups AfriForum and Solidarity which resulted in a boycott against the restaurant chain.

Gender activist and Sonke's Community Education and Mobilisation Unit Manager Nonhlanhla Skosana said Spur should "take full responsibility when a similar or worse incident happens in the future given that they have moved away from finding a lasting solution to this challenge."

'The cancellation of the panel came as a confirmation of Sonke Gender Justice's initial doubts in Spur's commitment to safety and anti-racism," according to the organisation's Sonke's Government and Media Liaison Patrick Godana.

"We were encouraged by the opportunity to work with a large company to prevent violence in their spaces, and to combat racism actively." Godana added.

The panel was expected to make recommendations to Spur on actions that should be taken to improve its reaction to similar incidents in future, after meetings which were scheduled to take place in the first week of October.

"If you look at the video both of them are perpetrators and both of them should be punished, if you have a person misbehaving and you simply want to say it is acceptable because she is black."

Both Solidarity and AfriForum have rejected claims that they have a role in driving Spur to cancel the panel.

"I don't think Solidarity has a racist culture so I think it is an unfounded comment," according to the trade union's Financial Services MD Francios Smit.

He said they had no power to direct Spur on what to do.

"I did not even know about the cancellation of the panel ..We cannot tell a company what to do," Smit said.

He goes on to deny that Solidarity had anything to do with the boycott against the restaurant.

"We never supported any boycott, we did not have a discussion with anybody about a boycott...I think the whole boycott argument is unfounded," he explained.

AfriForum CEO Kallie Kriel said the cases they handle show that they are not racist and has labelled Sonke Gender Justice as "uninformed".

"We acted of Gabriella Engels...we busy acting on behalf of people in Nkandla," he said.

He maintains that Spur should have "punished" both patrons instead of just Viljoen.

"If you look at the video both of them are perpetrators and both of them should be punished, if you have a person misbehaving and you simply want to say it is acceptable because she is black," he explained.

Spur declines to comment

Spur headquarters employee, Gayle Michelson on Friday said the company would not be making further comments on the matter.

"Mr Van Tonder told me to tell you that we won't be making any further comments," she said.

When HuffPost SA explained that it would be continue investigating the matter regardless of Spur's unwillngness to comment Michelson said, "you are putting me in a tight position".

We tried to reach CEO Pierre Van Tonder over 15 times on his cellphone since Monday with no response.

The initial call was made on Monday when he said he was in a meeting and we should call after midday. However, he has not answered his phone ever since.

We also tried to call the head of communications Moshe Apleni six times on Friday morning with no luck, however he remains active of his Whatsapp.

E-mails were also sent to both Michelson and Apleni about a response regarding the matter. Michelson has not sent a formal response and Apleni automated response said he was in training for the week.
