-Title- 
Twitter Plans To Introduce New Measures To Stamp Out Hate And Abuse
-Keywords-
['saw', 'abuse', 'safety', 'jack', 'twitter', 'email', 'rules', 'hate', 'silencing', 'rose', 'plans', 'measures', 'stamp', 'introduce', 'proposed', 'wired', 'voices']
-SUMMARY ARTICLE-
Twitter is planning to strengthen its policies as part of a massive shakeup that the social media giant hopes will assist in stamping out hate and abuse on its platform.
Following a boycott by female users after Rose McGowan's account was suspended amid accusations of rape against Harvey Weinstein, the company's CEO said that it was still "not doing enough" after it saw "voices silencing themselves".
"New rules around: unwanted sexual advances, non-consensual nudity, hate symbols, violent groups, and tweets that glorifies violence.
4/ Today we saw voices silencing themselves and voices speaking out because we're *still* not doing enough.
Here's a full copy of the e-mail and proposed changes obtained by Wired:
-TEXT INSIDE ARTICLE-
Twitter is planning to strengthen its policies as part of a massive shakeup that the social media giant hopes will assist in stamping out hate and abuse on its platform.

Following a boycott by female users after Rose McGowan's account was suspended amid accusations of rape against Harvey Weinstein, the company's CEO said that it was still "not doing enough" after it saw "voices silencing themselves".

to the women who boycotted, and the #woc who spoke up: I commend you for your disruption, dissent, and for hearing we who have been silenced — rose mcgowan (@rosemcgowan) October 14, 2017

"We decided to take a more aggressive stance in our rules and how we enforce them," Jack Dorsey tweeted on Saturday.

"New rules around: unwanted sexual advances, non-consensual nudity, hate symbols, violent groups, and tweets that glorifies violence. These changes will start rolling out in the next few weeks."

4/ Today we saw voices silencing themselves and voices speaking out because we're *still* not doing enough. — jack (@jack) October 14, 2017

Dorsey then linked to an article by Wired on Wednesday which contained an e-mail sent by Twitter's head of safety policy to the company's Trust and Safety Council seeking "critical feedback" on the proposed reforms.

"We have to do a better job explaining our policies and setting expectations for acceptable behaviour on our service," the e-mail said.

"We have a lot of work ahead of us and will definitely be turning to you all for guidance in the weeks ahead. We will do our best to keep you looped in on our progress."

Among the proposed reforms include immediately and permanently suspending accounts identified as sharing non-consensual nudity including "creep shots" and hidden camera content, as well as material intended to harass.

